{
  "texts": [
    "In contrast, ISAC first establishes the correct number of instance structures and only then binds semantics.",
    "This ensures reliable instance discrimination while requiring only minimal instance-count cues (see Tab.",
    "1).Layout-to-image methods Token-level semantics in text prompts lack instance discriminative cues, making additional layout conditions (e.g., bounding boxes) appealing.",
    "Box layouts are lightweight and, combined with the spatial understanding of large language models (LLMs), support a two-stage pipeline that first generates a bounding-box layout from text and then conditions image synthesis on that layout [22,23].",
    "While state-of-the-art controllers provide dense layout control [12,[24][25][26][27][28], they often struggle with overlapping layouts [29,30].Training-free layout-to-image methods [31][32][33][34][35][36][37][38] help, yet they do not ensure instance discrimination."
  ]
}